###  https://sakuna.ph/SuddenSubsidenceDry
:SuddenSubsidenceDry rdf:type owl:Class ;
                     rdfs:subClassOf :MassMovementDry ;
                     rdfs:label "Sudden Subsidence (Dry)"@en ;
                     skos:definition "Sudden subsidence (dry): Sinking of the ground due to groundwater removal, mining, dissolution of limestone (e.g., karst sinkholes), extraction of natural gas, and earthquakes. In this case, the sinking occurs under dry conditions as a result of a geophysical trigger. Can involve liquefaction and can be due to earthquakes." .


###  https://sakuna.ph/SuddenSubsidenceWet
:SuddenSubsidenceWet rdf:type owl:Class ;
                     rdfs:subClassOf :MassMovementWet ;
                     rdfs:label "Sudden Subsidence (Wet)"@en ;
                     skos:definition "Sudden subsidence (wet): Sinking of the ground like liquefaction near rivers or seas due to groundwater removal, mining, dissolution of limestone (e.g., karst sinkholes), extraction of natural gas, and earthquakes. In this case, the sinking occurs under wet conditions as a result of a hydrological trigger (e.g., rain). Can be due to tropical cyclones, stroms, depressions as well." .


